{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651764"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:27:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:27:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18493"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18493"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76760"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11222"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62253"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7522"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26324"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76760"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior segment of the eye contains several important structures and spaces that are essential for normal vision and intraocular pressure regulation. The anterior chamber of the eye is one of the structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its location?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Between the cornea and iris","Between the sclera and choroid","Between the iris and lens","Between the retina and choroid","Between the lens and vitreous humour"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebetween the cornea and iris\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the location of the anterior chamber of the eye (Image). This space is filled with aqueous humour and is crucial for maintaining intraocular pressure and providing nutrients to the avascular cornea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the sclera and choroid\u003C/strong\u003E - These layers are in direct contact with no intervening space\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the iris and lens\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the posterior chamber of the eye\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the retina and choroid\u003C/strong\u003E - This space does not exist as these layers are in direct contact\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the lens and vitreous humour\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no chamber here; the lens is in direct contact with the vitreous\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior chamber communicates with the posterior chamber through the pupil, allowing aqueous humour to flow from its site of production in the posterior chamber to its site of drainage in the anterior chamber angle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The anterior chamber of the eye lies between the cornea and iris.","The posterior chamber lies between the iris and lens.","Aqueous humour is produced in the posterior chamber and flows through the pupil into the anterior chamber."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cFlow of aqueous humour eye EDA02\u201d by National Eye Institute, National Institutes of Health is under\u00a0Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Flow_of_aqueous_humour_eye_EDA02.JPG\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62253"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18493"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21400"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21400"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/x4ZlUMAHpWd0caOUPaNJ4bQZvgj1br.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/x4ZlUMAHpWd0caOUPaNJ4bQZvgj1br.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":460}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62253"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T08:17:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T08:18:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11222"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76760"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null}